# Dome-World
just one of my ideas

Boozhoo // Bonjour // Hello my friend Premier Danielle Smith,
I would like to add one further note on so-called institutional neutrality for your consideration. I ask for grace if I am in any way unclear. In Ontario we are fluent in neither French nor inlgish, but I will do my best to get my point across with the language I have access to. Words are the first weapon which we reach for in a conflict, so I will draw mine out in the tradition of the "Irrepressible Letter Writer," Hidatsa leader Chief Wolf, who wrote persistently to successive presidents saying, "I wish to shake hands with the new Great Father," to demand that those who seek to govern his people look him in the eye before they would have him bow.
I speak from some personal familiarity with the machinery of institutional narrative. I was privileged to study corporate communication and public relations at Fanshawe College during the 2008 financial crisis, at a time when the Arab Spring first showed us how social media could be used to move masses of people and topple governments. As Occupy Wall Street rose up in response to reckless financial institutions and the institutions which were supposed to regulate them, I witnessed classmates set up tents and free libraries in Victoria Park and read their names in the news when the police came to shut it down. What stayed in my memory was the way that Occupy Wall Street's core calls for action were dismissed by the media as unrealistic simply because they had not been packaged in actionable administrative language. For this reason, the document which you are now reading arrives with appendixes, addendums, architectural principles, diagrams, and practical legislative steps. This correspondence is not a vague invitation to imagine a better world than we currently inhabit, but an announcement that the future we always dreamed possible has arrived in the flesh with specific proposals offered in a form that institutions can read. 
My submission is as follows:
Opening Letter — A reflection on institutional neutrality, professional regulation, and the historical context within which regulatory bodies claim authority, prompted by recent public debate regarding Peterson v. College of Psychologists of Ontario.
Appendix A: Flow-Core Framework — An interpretive systems framework offered as a lens for identifying bureaucratic inertia and delayed institutional feedback before crises cascade. It may complement existing analytical tools in areas including addiction services, mental health, and regulatory reform.
Appendix B: Children's Liberation and Dome-World Infrastructure — A legislative invitation to reconsider compulsory schooling frameworks, institutional claims on children's time, and community infrastructure design, with reference to established and proven education models (Montessori, Waldorf, Reggio Emilia) and Indigenous architectural traditions. Introduces the sheltered atrium as the architectural expression of Flow-Core principles.
Appendix C: Infrastructural Sovereignty — A legislative framework for decentralized, water-based hydraulic systems grounded in UP//DOWN gravitational storage, tendency settling, and Flow-Core Governance. Extends Dome-World principles from children's spaces to full community energy and resource autonomy.
Appendix D: Mental Health Transition and Relational Care — A legislative framework for transitioning Alberta's mental health system from a predominantly biomedical model toward relational, community-based care, with phased funding redistribution, informed consent standards, and Indigenous mental health sovereignty.
Appendix E: Ambient Cognition and AI Governance — An orientation to the governance challenges presented by distributed artificial intelligence systems, including the energy demands of AI infrastructure, specific risks warranting legislative attention (including cognitive warfare through personal channels), and principles for adaptive regulatory response.
Appendix F: Dual Justice and Legal Pluralism — A Flow-Core invitation to establish a parallel justice system administered by Treaty partners, addressing court backlogs, operationalizing genuine neutrality, and honouring the legal traditions that predate the Crown.
I write not as a representative of any organization, but as a constituent engaged in good faith with the philosophical and practical foundations of policy. The proposals offered are specific and actionable, and I have included citations and evidence throughout to support further review by the relevant ministries. I respectfully invite your office to direct the appropriate sections to the Ministries of Health, Education, Technology and Innovation, Indigenous Relations, Energy, Municipal Affairs, and Infrastructure as warranted by their respective mandates. I would welcome the opportunity for dialogue with any member of your team who wishes to explore these ideas further.
